@DATABASE "Reminder"
@MASTER "ReminderMainGuide"
@NODE MAIN "Reminder  -  http://chebucto.ns.ca/~ah210/reminder.html"
                           @{FG shine}Reminder Version 0.9B@{FG text}
                      -------------------------------

  Thank you for trying Reminder!  Although it is @{b}still@{ub} in a Beta stage
  (as is this document), it is stable enough (I hope!) to use on a day
  to day basis.

  Click one of the following buttons to read that section.


         @{"Legal Stuff" link LEGAL}   Please read this first!

         @{"Introduction" link intro}  A quick overview.

         @{"Requirements" link requirements}  What you need.

         @{"Installation" link install}  Where everything goes.

         @{"Usage" link usage}         How to make it go.



  This is the last (but also the first!) version of @{"Reminder" link CX} in its present
  form.  I plan to rewrite Reminder either in BlitzII again, or in C, so that
  it will be more flexible than it is now.  For example, instead of being
  confined to having a reminder displayed every day, month, year, etc, you will
  be able to have a message displayed in any combination of years, months,
  days, and more!  It should make it easier to add new ways of reminding,
  perhaps using separate "modules" that you can make yourself!

  But, I'm getting ahead of myself.  I hope you enjoy Reminder, and please
  @{"let me know" link CONTACT} what you think of it.  Keep an eye on the Reminder
  homepage at http://chebucto.ns.ca/~ah210/reminder.html.





@ENDNODE
@NODE INTRO "Introduction"

  @{"Reminder" link CX} was born when I couldn't find a program anywhere that did what it
  does - remind me of upcoming events, things to do, things to remember,
  etc.  There were plenty of naggers out there, but none of them scrolled
  a message across the screen (which I thought was a neat idea :)
  and were nice and simple to use like I've tried to make Reminder.

  Using a small and simple GUI, you can enter your own messages and tell
  Reminder when and how you want them to be displayed.  The text of your
  message will be scrolled across the Workbench screen, and can be accompanied
  by a sampled sound, digitized speech, the execution of another program,
  the system beep, a music module, or nothing at all.  You can also opt to
  have no message, so that the only reminder you get is a sound or a beep, etc.

@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUIREMENTS "What you need to run Reminder"

  To run @{"Reminder" link CX} you need:

  An Amiga computer (or 100% compatible :)
  A battery-backed-up clock in your Amiga
  Kickstart 2 or greater
  512K of RAM should do

  Reminder was tested on:

  Amiga 500 with 1 megabyte chip RAM, 6 megabytes fast RAM, an M-Tec
  68020i accelerator with a 68881 math co-processor, Kickstart 39.106, and
  a 170 megabyte hard drive.  The development machine.

  Amiga 500 with 1 megabyte chip RAM, 2 megabytes fast RAM,
  Kickstart 37.175, and an 80 megabyte hard drive.

  Amiga 1200 with 2 megs chip RAM, and a 200 megabyte hard drive.

@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "Installing Reminder"

  Installing @{"Reminder" link CX} is a simple as dragging the ReminderPrefs icon into your
  prefs drawer (usually located on your system or boot drive), and the
  ReminderCX icon to anywhere, although I recommend placing it in the WBStartup
  drawer of your boot drive.  This way, Reminder will be run each time you boot
  your Amiga.
@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE "Using Reminder"

  Reminder is split into two programs.  Each one is documented separately.

  @{"ReminderPrefs" link PREFS}  The preferences editor.

  @{"ReminderCX" link CX}  The main program, which does the reminding.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFS "ReminderPrefs - The Reminder Preferences Editor"

                                ReminderPrefs
                              -----------------

  ReminderPrefs lets you add, delete, and edit the messages that @{"Reminder" link CX}
  displays.  When you run the program by double-clicking its icon, you will
  see a window listing the reminders that have been saved.  If this is the first
  time you have used Reminder, you will see a message that says "No Reminders"
  under the listbox.

  To choose a reminder, simply click on it in the listbox, and its name
  will be shown in the text field under the listbox. If there are more
  reminders than can be shown at once, you can use the scroller on the right
  hand side of the listbox to move up and down in the list.

                     Under the listbox there are seven gadgets:

                          @{"Add" link prefsadd}  @{"Remove" link prefsremove}  @{"Edit" link prefsedit}  @{"Test" link prefstest}

                        @{"  Save  " link prefssave}  @{"  Use  " link prefsuse}  @{" Cancel " link prefscancel}

  There are also two menus in ReminderPrefs' title bar, the Project and Edit
  menus.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Project@{FG TEXT}

   Open...       This option allows you to open a previously saved settings
                 file.  This can be the default "Reminder.prefs" which is
                 stored in the ENVARC: directory, or another file which
                 was saved using the Save or Save As option (see below).

   Save          This option will save the current settings.  If you have not
                 already saved them, a file requester will open to allow you
                 to give a filename, otherwise the last filename given will be
                 used.

   Save As...    This option will save the current settings.  A file requester
                 will be opened to allow you to choose a directory and filename
                 for the settings.  You can then open the settings later using
                 the Open option, above.

   About...      This option gives you information on the version of @{"Reminder" link CX}
                 and ReminderPrefs you are using.

   Quit...       This option is the same as clicking the @{"Cancel" link PrefsCancel} button
                 on the ReminderPrefs main window, except you will be asked
                 if you want to quit first.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Edit@{FG TEXT}

   Delete ALL    This option will erase ALL reminders at once.  You will be
   Reminders     asked if you really want to do this, just in case you don't.

   Last Saved    This option restores the settings that were last saved
                 using the @{"Save" link prefssave} button on the ReminderPrefs main window.

  Restore        This option restores the settings that were present before
                 any changes were made.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSADD "ReminderPrefs: Adding Reminders"

  The Add button of ReminderPrefs adds a new reminder to the list of reminders.
  When you add a reminder, the @{"Edit" link prefsedit} window will be opened,
  which will let you customize the reminder to your liking.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSREMOVE "ReminderPrefs: Removing Reminders"

  To remove a reminder, simply select it from the list of reminders, and click
  the Remove gadget.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSEDIT "ReminderPrefs:  Editing Reminders"
  The edit window, once opened, allows you to customize the currently selected
  reminder.  Here you can change the text of the reminder, set the font and
  colour of the reminder, among other things.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Message Text @{FG TEXT}  This gadget contains the text that will be displayed within
                 the reminder.  To enter text for your reminder, simply click
                 in this gadget and type your message.

                 If you leave this gadget blank, then no message will be
                 displayed.  This allows you to use the extra notification (see
                 below) without having a message displayed.

                 @{"Reminder" link CX} also supports importing the first line of text from
                 one or more files.  To do this, enclose the name of the file
                 which you wish to import text from in double percent signs.
                 For example, to include the first line of a file called
                 message, you could do enter something like this:

                 @{FG SHINE}Quote of the day: @{FG HIGHLIGHT}%%@{FG SHINE}message@{FG HIGHLIGHT}%%@{FG TEXT}

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Font@{FG TEXT}           This gadget, when clicked, will open a standard Amiga font
                 requester.  You can use this to select which font, style, and
                 colours will be used to display your message.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Display@{FG TEXT}        This cycle gadget determines how frequently the reminder
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Message@{FG TEXT}        will be displayed.  Hopefully it's self-explanatory.
                 Some options can be reset or set to certain values, see the
                 @{FG fill}Set/Reset@{FG TEXT} gadget below.

                 @{FG fill}* BETA NOTE *@{FG TEXT}  The "randomly" option is not
                 yet optional, and therefore has no effect at this time.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Set/Reset@{FG TEXT}      This gadget will allow you to set or reset certain
                 types of reminders.  For reminders that display their message
                 @{FG FILL}every x minutes@{FG TEXT}, or @{FG FILL}at HH:MM:SS@{FG TEXT}, you can set the interval or
                 the time for the message by clicking this gadget.

                 For the other two types of reminder that this gadget applies
                 to, @{FG fill}each year@{FG text} and @{FG fill}each month@{FG TEXT}, you can reset the message to the
                 beginning of the year or month so that instead of appearing
                 every 12 months (1 year) or every 31 days, it will appear
                 every January 1st, or at the beginning of each month.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Seconds Pause@{FG TEXT}  This numeric gadget determines how long (in seconds) @{"Reminder" link CX}
                 will pause when the message has reached the middle
                 of screen.  A value of -1 will cause Reminder to wait
                 forever, or until someone clicks the reminder's close gadget.

                 @{FG FILL}! Warning !@{FG TEXT} - It is possible to create a reminder
                 that will never go away by choosing a value of -1 and
                 not having the window's close gadget (see below) turned on.
                 This is, of course, a feature, not a bug! :)

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Scroll Delay@{FG TEXT}   This numeric gadget determines how fast the message text
                 scrolls across the screen.  A higher number causes slower
                 scrolling.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Window Close@{FG TEXT}   This checkbox, when checked, will give the reminder's
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Gadget      @{FG TEXT}   window a close gadget which you can use to close the
                 reminder before it scrolls off the screen.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Time Frame@{FG TEXT}     This cycle gadget controls when the reminder will appear.
                 The options are:

                 @{FG SHINE}Always@{FG TEXT} - The reminder will always be displayed,
                          as long as the condition in the Display Message
                          gadget is met.

                 @{FG SHINE}Range@{FG TEXT}  - The reminder will be displayed if the
                          current date is within the range set in the range
                          gadgets (see below) and the condition in the display
                          message gadget is met.

              @{FG SHINE}Sunday to@{FG TEXT} - The reminder will be displayed if
              @{FG SHINE}Saturday@{FG TEXT}    the day of the week is the one selected,
                          and, as usual, the condition in the display
                          message gadget is met.

                 @{FG SHINE}Never@{FG TEXT}  - The reminder will never be displayed, @{b}no matter what@{ub}.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Range@{FG TEXT}          These gadgets determine the range of dates in which the
                 reminder will be displayed.  Note that the first date should be
                 earlier than the second, otherwise you may encounter unexpected
                 results.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Extra@{FG TEXT}          This section allows you to add a special event to
                 the reminder when it scrolls to the centre of the screen.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Type@{FG TEXT}           This cycle gadget determines what type of event
                 will occur when the reminder reaches the centre of the screen.
                 Note that the @{FG SHINE}Speak Text@{FG TEXT} event requires the
                 files LIBS:translator.library and L:speak-handler.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}File@{FG TEXT}           This text gadget allows you to enter an external
                 filename to use with the events @{FG SHINE}Play IFF Sample, Play
                 Music Module, and External Program@{FG TEXT}.

                   The @{FG SHINE}External Program@{FG TEXT} event has a special feature.
                   If you wish to execute more than one program,
                   simply separate each one with an ampersand. For example,
                   to run the programs "one" and "two", you would enter:

                   @{FG SHINE}one@{FG HIGHLIGHT}&@{FG SHINE}two@{FG TEXT}

                   Note that this will execute the programs one by one,
                   that is, "two" will begin when "one" has finished.
                   To avoid this, insert the command RUN before each
                   program name, like this:

                   @{FG SHINE}RUN one@{FG HIGHLIGHT}&@{FG SHINE}RUN two@{FG TEXT}

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}^@{FG TEXT}             This small gadget at the far right of the file gadget
                opens a file requester which allows you to select a file name to
                insert into the file gadget.

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Test@{FG TEXT}           This gadget will test the extra notification event
                that is currently selected.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSTEST "ReminderPrefs: Testing Reminders"

  This button will display the currently selected reminder exactly as it would
  be shown normally.  This allows you to test your settings whenever you wish.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSSAVE "ReminderPrefs : The Save Button"

  This button, as in most preferences programs, saves your settings
  so that they will be ready the next time you use either @{"Reminder" link CX} or
  ReminderPrefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSUSE "ReminderPrefs : The Use Button"

  This button, as in most preferences programs, keeps your settings
  for the time being, but as soon as you reboot or turn of your Amiga,
  they will be lost forever.  They can still be saved or changed,
  simply by re-opening ReminderPrefs.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PREFSCANCEL "ReminderPrefs : The Cancel Button"

  This button, as in most preferences programs, will close ReminderPrefs,
  and any changes you made will be lost.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CX "ReminderCX - Reminder Itself"

                                   ReminderCX
                                 --------------

  ReminderCX, unlike @{"ReminderPrefs" link PREFS}, does not have a Graphical
  User Interface (GUI).  Once it has been run, it sits in the background,
  waiting until it is time to display one of its messages, known as reminders.

  ReminderCX is a commodity, which means you can control it using the Amiga's
  Exchange program.  Exchange allows you to do three thing with Reminder.
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}
  If you don't know how to run Exchange, click @{"here" SYSTEM "RUN `SEARCH SYS: FILE ALL Exchange`"} and
  I'll try to find it and run it on your boot partition or drive.

  Click @{"here" SYSTEM "echo > CON:0/80//120/Exchange-located!/CLOSE/AUTO/WAIT Your Exchange is `search sys: exchange all file`."} and I'll tell you where you can find Exchange!


  @{FG TEXT}
    Activate / Inactive - This cycle gadget lets you turn Reminder 'on' and
                          'off'.  If you change Reminder's status to
                          "Inactive", it is still running, but no reminders
                          will be displayed.

    Show Interface      - This gadget will open ReminderPrefs, if it is located
                          in the SYS:Prefs drawer.  Note that for now, Reminder
                          must be quit and re-run to notice any changes you
                          may make.

    Remove              - This is the only way to quit Reminder.  Once you
                          click this button, Reminder will be removed, no
                          questions asked.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CONTACT "Contacting the author"

  If you have any trouble using Reminder, or suggestions, comments, or
  bugs to report, or anything else to say, please feel free to contact me!

  My email address is ah210@chebucto.ns.ca, and if you are ever on IRC,
  you can usually find me on the undernet, in #amiga or #AmIRC, as Merc.

  You can also read the latest on Reminder and my other projects on my homepage
  at http://chebucto.ns.ca/~ah210/reminder.html.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}NOTE:@{FG TEXT}  When reporting bugs, or problems, please
         tell me what Amiga model you have, what software you are running,
         what versions of Workbench and Kickstart you're running, etc.
         This will make it much easier for me to locate the problem.


@ENDNODE
